Identity and access management access analyzer.

Access analyzer watches your account for two kinds of drift: unintended openness, and permissions wandering away from least privilege.

Its external-access feature continuously inspects resource policies, on buckets, roles, keys, functions, queues, and secrets, and flags anything reachable from outside your account or organization. So if a bucket policy accidentally opens to the world, you hear about it.

Its unused-access feature flags users, roles, permissions, and access keys that haven't been touched recently, which is how you find and trim the permissions nobody actually needs.

Policy validation checks the policies you write before you deploy them, catching syntax problems, redundant statements, and best-practice violations. And policy generation goes a step further: it reads your audit-trail history for an identity and proposes a tighter policy based on what that identity actually used. Together, these turn least privilege from a one-time aspiration into something you can continuously measure.
